REPORT 7 — Singapore PDPA Consent Flow Audit (Mobile App Scenario)
Title: Consent Flow Privacy Audit for Mobile Fintech Application — PDPA Compliance Review
Region: Asia-Pacific (Singapore)
Industry: Fintech / Mobile Applications
Author: Ssambra — Identity Auditor & Threat Sentinel

1. Executive Summary
A Singapore-based fintech startup launched a mobile budgeting app that collects:

Bank transaction data

Spending categories

Location data

Behavioral analytics

During a routine privacy review, it was discovered that the app’s consent flow did not meet PDPA requirements, specifically:

Consent was bundled instead of granular

Purpose statements were vague

Location tracking was enabled by default

Withdrawal of consent required emailing support

No retention schedule was disclosed

This audit evaluates the app’s consent mechanisms against the Personal Data Protection Act (PDPA) and provides actionable recommendations.

2. Background
The app uses open banking APIs to aggregate financial data.
To personalize insights, it also collects:

Location data

Device identifiers

Spending behavior patterns

A user complaint triggered the audit:

“I didn’t know the app was tracking my location even when closed.”

Your role:

Review the consent flow

Identify PDPA violations

Evaluate UX and behavioral risks

Recommend remediation steps

3. Scope
This audit covers:

Consent collection

Purpose limitation

Notification obligations

Withdrawal of consent

Data retention

UX patterns that influence user behavior

4. Consent Flow Review
Observed User Journey
User installs the app

Onboarding screen requests:

Access to bank data

Access to location

Permission for “personalization”

All toggles default to ON

No explanation of data retention

Withdrawal of consent requires emailing support

Privacy policy is 18 pages long and written at a university reading level

5. Findings (Mapped to PDPA Requirements)
Finding 1 — Consent Not Granular
PDPA Requirement:  
Consent must be specific and unbundled.

Issue:  
Bank data, location data, and behavioral analytics were grouped under one toggle.

Risk:  
Users cannot meaningfully choose what they agree to.

Severity: High

Finding 2 — Vague Purpose Statements
PDPA Requirement:  
Organizations must state clear purposes for data collection.

Issue:  
“Personalization” was used as a catch‑all term.

Risk:  
Users cannot understand how their data is used.

Severity: Medium

Finding 3 — Location Tracking Enabled by Default
PDPA Requirement:  
Consent must be voluntary and not obtained through deceptive design.

Issue:  
Location tracking toggle defaulted to ON.

Risk:  
Perceived dark pattern; regulatory scrutiny.

Severity: High

Finding 4 — Withdrawal of Consent Not Reasonably Accessible
PDPA Requirement:  
Withdrawal must be as easy as giving consent.

Issue:  
Users must email support to revoke permissions.

Risk:  
Non‑compliance; user frustration.

Severity: Medium

Finding 5 — No Data Retention Disclosure
PDPA Requirement:  
Organizations must disclose retention periods or criteria.

Issue:  
Retention not mentioned anywhere in the app.

Risk:  
Regulatory violation; user distrust.

Severity: High

6. Human Behavior Analysis (Psychology Lens)
Dark Pattern Risk
Default‑on toggles exploit status quo bias, nudging users to accept more data collection than intended.

Cognitive Overload
Long privacy policy + vague language increases decision fatigue, reducing meaningful consent.

Trust Erosion
Users feel “tricked” when discovering hidden tracking, reducing long‑term retention.

7. Recommendations
Governance Controls
Rewrite purpose statements in plain language

Document lawful basis for each data type

Establish PDPA‑aligned retention schedule

UX & Consent Controls
Separate toggles for:

Bank data

Location data

Behavioral analytics

Default all toggles to OFF

Add “Why we need this” micro‑explanations

Provide in‑app consent withdrawal

Technical Controls
Implement location tracking only when app is active

Log consent changes for auditability

Automate data deletion based on retention schedule

